ink":null},"annotations":{"bold":false,"italic":false,"strikethrough":false,"underline":false,"code":false,"color":"default"},"plain_text":"” tire section height and the “","href":null}],"icon":null,"color":"default"},"archived":false},{"object":"block","id":"35534d6d-7cea-81c1-88e1-c698110281ff","parent":{"type":"page_id","page_id":"35534d6d-7cea-81c0-b78b-f1de4c0a9140"},"created_time":"2026-05-03T22:03:00.000Z","last_edited_time":"2026-05-03T22:03:00.000Z","created_by":{"object":"user","id":"35534d6d-7cea-8179-8809-002768bc44c3"},"last_edited_by":{"object":"user","id":"35534d6d-7cea-8179-8809-002768bc44c3"},"has_children":false,"in_trash":false,"type":"paragraph","paragraph":{"rich_text":[{"type":"text","text":{"content":"under-load","link":null},"annotations":{"bold":false,"italic":false,"strikethrough":false,"underline":false,"code":false,"color":"default"},"plain_text":"under-load","href":null}],"icon":null,"color":"default"},"archived":false},{"object":"block","id":"35534d6d-7cea-8138-83b0-d68f8d637722","parent":{"type":"page_id","page_id":"35534d6d-7cea-81c0-b78b-f1de4c0a9140"},"created_time":"2026-05-03T22:03:00.000Z","last_edited_time":"2026-05-03T22:03:00.000Z","created_by":{"object":"user","id":"35534d6d-7cea-8179-8809-002768bc44c3"},"last_edited_by":{"object":"user","id":"35534d6d-7cea-8179-8809-002768bc44c3"},"has_children":false,"in_trash":false,"type":"paragraph","paragraph":{"rich_text":[{"type":"text","text":{"content":"” tire section height, normally measured from tread face / shoulder to the wheel flange. The deflection amount or percentage is the difference in the two heights.\n\nSometimes, tires may appear to be under-inflated, when in fact they are “deflecting” at the sidewall to ensure the tread face is providing the maximum ground contact for maximum performance.","link":null},"annotations":{"bold":false,"italic":false,"strikethrough":false,"underline":false,"code":false,"color":"default"},"plain_text":"” tire section height, normally measured from tread face / shoulder to the wheel flange. The deflection amount or percentage is the difference in the two heights.\n\nSometimes, tires may appear to be under-inflated, when in fact they are “deflecting” at the sidewall to ensure the tread face is providing the maximum ground contact for maximum performance.","href":null}],"icon":null,"color":"default"},"archived":false},{"object":"block","id":"35534d6d-7cea-811c-9fec-f8f6c3708bde","parent":{"type":"page_id","page_id":"35534d6d-7cea-81c0-b78b-f1de4c0a9140"},"created_time":"2026-05-03T22:03:00.000Z","last_edited_time":"2026-05-03T22:03:00.000Z","created_by":{"object":"user","id":"35534d6d-7cea-8179-8809-002768bc44c3"},"last_edited_by":{"object":"user","id":"35534d6d-7cea-8179-8809-002768bc44c3"},"has_children":false,"in_trash":false,"type":"heading_2","heading_2":{"rich_text":[{"type":"text","text":{"content":"Optimal Tire Deflection for Agriculture","link":null},"annotations":{"bold":false,"italic":false,"strikethrough":false,"underline":false,"code":false,"color":"default"},"plain_text":"Optimal Tire Deflection for Agriculture","href":null}],"is_toggleable":false,"color":"default"},"archived":false},{"object":"block","id":"35534d6d-7cea-8126-bd15-d3acf388f4eb","parent":{"type":"page_id","page_id":"35534d6d-7cea-81c0-b78b-f1de4c0a9140"},"created_time":"2026-05-03T22:03:00.000Z","last_edited_time":"2026-05-03T22:03:00.000Z","created_by":{"object":"user","id":"35534d6d-7cea-8179-8809-002768bc44c3"},"last_edited_by":{"object":"user","id":"35534d6d-7cea-8179-8809-002768bc44c3"},"has_children":false,"in_trash":false,"type":"paragraph","paragraph":{"rich_text":[{"type":"text","text":{"content":"As the tire compresses or deflects under the given load, the tire footprint extends to ensure the tread face provides as much ground contact as possible.\n\nThe “optimal” tire deflection in an agricultural tire ensures that the tire properly compresses to apply the right amount of pressure and contact to the soil beneath it.\n\nIf the tires are under light load, the footprint becomes smaller as the sidewall deflection is minimal. As the weight or load increases on the tire, the deflection increases, and the tire footprint becomes longer along the tread face contacting the soil.","link":null},"annotations":{"bold":false,"italic":false,"strikethrough":false,"underline":false,"code":false,"color":"default"},"plain_text":"As the tire compresses or deflects under the given load, the tire footprint extends to ensure the tread face provides as much ground contact as possible.\n\nThe “optimal” tire deflection in an agricultural tire ensures that the tire properly compresses to apply the right amount of pressure and contact to the soil beneath it.\n\nIf the tires are under light load, the footprint becomes smaller as the sidewall deflection is minimal. As the weight or load increases on the tire, the deflection increases, and the tire footprint becomes longer along the tread face contacting the soil.","href":null}],"icon":null,"color":"default"},"archived":false},{"object":"block","id":"35534d6d-7cea-81d0-a643-c0f395647864","parent":{"type":"page_id","page_id":"35534d6d-7cea-81c0-b78b-f1de4c0a9140"},"created_time":"2026-05-03T22:03:00.000Z","last_edited_time":"2026-05-03T22:03:00.000Z","created_by":{"object":"user","id":"35534d6d-7cea-8179-8809-002768bc44c3"},"last_edited_by":{"object":"user","id":"35534d6d-7cea-8179-8809-002768bc44c3"},"has_children":false,"in_trash":false,"type":"heading_2","heading_2":{"rich_text":[{"type":"text","text":{"content":"Benefits of Optimizing Tire Deflection","link":null},"annotations":{"bold":false,"italic":false,"strikethrough":false,"underline":false,"code":false,"color":"default"},"plain_text":"Benefits of Optimizing Tire Deflection","href":null}],"is_toggleable":false,"color":"default"},"archived":false},{"object":"block","id":"35534d6d-7cea-8183-a8d4-f03471bcf9ae","parent":{"type":"page_id","page_id":"35534d6d-7cea-81c0-b78b-f1de4c0a9140"},"created_time":"